orm with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Ieuan ap Hywel was born about 1360, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 6 sons and 1 daughter with Hywel ap Gwilym."},"et":{"Abt 1360–":"umbes 1360–Surnud","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1391–Male":"1391–Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","about 1391":"umbes 1391","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1360":"1360","Abt 1380":"umbes 1380","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","1438":"1438","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of Rhigos,Ystradyfodwg,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Rhigos, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Llantrisant,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Llantrisant, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1360–":"noin 1360–Kuollut","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1391–Male":"1391–Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","Abt 1360":"noin 1360","about 1391":"noin 1391","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","about 1400":"noin 1400","1360":"1360","Abt 1380":"noin 1380","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","1438":"1438","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of Rhigos,Ystradyfodwg,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Rhigos, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of,Llantrisant,Glamorganshire,Wales":"Llantrisant, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1360–":"environ 1360–Décédée","1365–1438":"1365–1438","1380–Male":"1380–Décédé","1391–Male":"1391–Décédé","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","Abt 1360":"environ 1360","about 1391":"environ 1391","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","about 1400":"environ 1400","1360":"1360","Abt 1380":"environ 1380","1391":"1391","1380":"1380","1438":"1438","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Pays